        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We have configured Baseband 1 to FDM-mode with a width of ~5000 km/s to obtain maximum continuum bandwidth and maximize the sensitivity for continuum observations, as we do not need very high spectral resolutions for our line observations. We expect the line widths of the CO(1-0) line to be similar to the ~ 60 km/s as observed in our Cycle 2 CO(3-2) spectra (e.g. Fig. 1, right). The spectral resolution of ~5 km/s after spectral averaging (to lower data rates) is thus sufficient for our purposes. We have also configured Baseband 3 to FDM-mode to detect the 13C18O emission line which may also be useful to better understand the gas conditions. The other two basebands are set to TDM mode for continuum observations and tuned such that we obtain the maximum 7.5 GHz bandwidth to give us maximum continuum sensitivity.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We selected the angular resolution of 0.3" so that our CO(1-0) map will be comparable in angular resolution to our Cycle 2 CO(3-2) map. This will also give us a good balance between angular resolution and surface brightness sensitivity to increase our chances of detecting the line emission. In our Cycle 2 observations, there were no components larger than ~1" per channel in the channel maps. We thus do not require additional observations from more compact configurations and the ACA.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The ALMA Cycle 2 observations of the CO(3-2) line show that the individual gas components have peak fluxes of about 4 mJy/beam, for beam sizes of ~0.3". We expect that the fluxes of the CO(1-0) line will be about a factor of 3 lower, if the line flux ratios are similar to that of the Milky Way. This will allow us to detect the CO(1-0) line at &gt; 3 sigma for our requested RMS of 0.35 mJy/beam. Should the line not be detected at these sensitivities, we can conclude that the gas conditions are warmer and more similar to that in starbursts and quasars - which is the aim of this science goal. The CO(3-2) line widths of the different components from our Cycle 2 observations are of order 60 km/s (e.,g. see Fig 1., right panel, in the science justification) and we expect the line widths to be similar for our CO(1-0) observations. It is therefore sufficient if the requested RMS is achieved at 20 km/s bandwidths.

If the (sub-)mm continuum emission in the central 100 pc is dominated by thermal dust emission, the expected flux density at 110 GHz is ~ 0.09 mJy, based on extrapolations from the 343 GHz Cycle 2 continuum flux. The predicted RMS over the 7.5 GHz continuum bandwidth is ~ 11 muJy/beam, allowing us to detect the signal at ~ 8sigma, assuming the source is unresolved. If the continuum emission is dominated by synchrotron emission, the predicted flux density will be ~1.75 mJy, and hence can be easily detected with a S/N of ~ 150. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
    </prj:ScienceGoal>
