        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We have configured Baseband 1 to FDM-mode with a width of ~834km/s to obtain maximum continuum bandwidth and maximize the sensitivity for continuum observations, as we do not need very high spectral resolutions for our line observations. We expect the line widths of the CO(6-5) line to be ~ 60 km/s as observed in our Cycle 2 CO(3-2) spectra (e.g., Fig. 1, right). The spectral resolution of ~3 km/s is sufficient for our purposes. The 834 km/s bandwidth is also sufficiently large to accomodate the velocity shifts of the different components (+-100km/s) with respect to the source recessional velocity. The other three basebands are set to TDM mode for continuum observations and tuned such that we will obtain the largest total bandwidth possible for maximum continuum sensitivity.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We selected the angular resolution of 0.1" to better resolve the structures in the gas ring, particularly that of the bright Western clump. This will also enable us to better constrain (if not detect) the gas mass in the inner ~50 pc, slightly closer to the black hole compared to our Cycle 2 observations. In our Cycle 2 observations, there were no components larger than ~1" per channel in the channel maps, hence ACA observations are not necessary. Also, for this science goal, the focus is on spatially resolving the structures in the gas ring, so more compact configurations are not necessary.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>If the CO(6-5) line flux is higher than that of CO(3-2) by a factor of 5 or more, as seen in nearby Seyferts, starbursts and QSOs, we will be able to detect the CO(6-5) line at ~ 6sigma for our requested RMS of 2.5 mJy/beam. Should the line not be detected at these sensitivities, we can conclude that the gas conditions are cooler and more similar to that in the Milky Way. We thus expect to detect at least the CO(1-0) line in Band 3 or the CO(6-5) line in this band, allowing us to place strong constraints on the gas excitation levels. The different gas components in our Cycle 2 CO(3-2) maps have line widths of order 60 km/s (e.g. Fig. 1, right, in the science justification) and we expect the line widths to be similar for our CO(6-5) observations. It is therefore sufficient to obtain the requested RMS at 20 km/s bandwidths.

If the (sub-)mm continuum emission in the central 100 pc is dominated by thermal dust emission, the expected flux density at 670 GHz is ~ 3.5 mJy, based on extrapolations from the 343 GHz Cycle 2 continuum flux. The predicted RMS over the 7.5 GHz continuum bandwidth is ~ 0.2 mJy/beam, allowing us to detect the signal at ~ 18 sigma, assuming the source is unresolved. If the continuum emission is dominated by synchrotron emission, the predicted flux will be ~ 0.4mJy, hence a non-detection will confirm this scenario.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
